# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: av2-codec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The **Alliance for Open Media** (**AOMedia**) is a non-profit industry consortium headquartered in Wakefield, Massachusetts, and formed to develop open, royalty-free technology for multimedia delivery.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] It uses the ideas and principles of open web standard development to create video standards that can serve as alternatives to the hitherto dominant standards of the Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG).
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Its first project was to develop AV1, a new open video codec and format, as a successor to VP9 and an alternative to HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] AV1 uses elements from Daala, Thor, and VP10, three preceding open video codecs.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The governing members of the Alliance for Open Media are Amazon, Apple, Cisco, Google, Intel, Meta Platforms, Microsoft, Mozilla, Netflix, Nvidia, Samsung Electronics and Tencent.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Some collaboration and work that would later be merged into AV1 predates the official launch of the Alliance.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] In May 2015, the Internet Video Codec working group (NetVC) of the IETF was officially started and presented with coding techniques from Daala.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Cisco Systems joined forces and offered their own prototype format Thor to the working group on July 22.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The lack of a suitable video format for inclusion in the specification of HTML video by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) and the failed negotiations for one mandatory video format for WebRTC showed the need for a competitive, open video standard.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The emergence of a second patent pool for HEVC (HEVC Advance) in spring 2015 provided motivation for investments in an alternative video format and grew support for the Alliance, mainly due to the uncertainty regarding royalties for MPEG's next-generation video format, HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] On September 1, 2015, the Alliance for Open Media was announced with the goal of developing a royalty-free video format as an alternative to licensed formats such as H.264 and HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The founding members are Amazon, Cisco, Google, Intel, Microsoft, Mozilla, and Netflix.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The plan was to release the video format by 2017.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The alliance saw expansion of its member list since inception.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] On April 5, 2016, the Alliance for Open Media announced that AMD, ARM, and Nvidia had joined, and Adobe, Ateme, Ittiam and Vidyo joined in the months following.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] On November 13, 2017, Facebook later joined as a governing member.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] In January 2018 the alliance's website was quietly updated to add Apple as a governing member of the alliance.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] On April 3, 2019, Samsung Electronics joined as a governing member.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] October 1, 2019, Tencent joined as a governing member.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Articles suggested that Google was in planning to release 2 open formats, High-dynamic-range video/HDR video and 3D audio, as alternatives to Dolby Atmos and Dolby Vision video technology.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] A draft called IAC has been developed for audio, and Samsung's HDR10+ will not be utilized.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] During September 2022, AOMedia announced Project Caviar.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Although the name is yet to be disclosed, the announcement was made public through a journal authored by AOMedia developers and biographies shared on the doc: and after a month papers calls were released with an early draft.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The Video Codec Working Group (CWG) was the first AOMedia technical group.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Recognizing some needs, AOMedia created, in February 2022, the Volumetric Visual Media Working Group (VVMWG).
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] In June 2022, 10 universities and 24 organizations (companies) went to Alliance for Open Media Symposium, with various engineers working on AV1 and developing the new technologies in the cwg incubators gains test for the Next Generation AOM standard.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] There are in the alliance efforts done through different working groups.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] AVM: AOM Video Model - was created in the AOMedia GitLab repository.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] It consists of tools based on research candidate.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] AVM is the software codebase that AOMedia is using for its research and development of the next generation video coding technologies.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The development happens in stages, and each new anchor is the codebase in which previously adopted experiments have been integrated and which is used in the following round of the experiments. - this repo based on Libaom, reference encoder for AV1 format.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] During June 2023, AOMedia announced that Zoom Video Communications would become a promoter member.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] AOMedia's first project was the creation of an open video compression format and codec optimized for streaming media over the internet, intended for both commercial and non-commercial content, including user-generated content.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The format is intended to be the first in a line of new, AOMedia Video (AV) formats being developed.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] AOMedia planned for the first version of its format (AV1) to be completed before the end of 2017.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] However, work on the bitstream specification will be continued into 2018.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The format is the primary contender for standardisation by the video coding standard working group NetVC of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The main distinguishing features of AV1 are its purported royalty-free licensing terms and performance.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] AV1 is specifically designed for real-time applications and for higher resolutions than typical usage scenarios of the current generation (H.264) of video formats.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] In 2019, Sisvel International formed a patent pool for selling licenses to intellectual property it anticipates will be necessary to comply with the AV1 standard.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] AOMedia said this was contrary to its goal of a standard developed entirely with free, donated technology owned by the organization.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Sisvel anticipates AV1 will require patented technology developed outside the AOMedia member organizations.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] In November 2023 IAMF (Immersive Audio Model and Formats) was announced.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] In February 2026 *Open Audio Codec* (*OAC*) had started development, based on the Opus source code and intended to be its successor.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The Alliance is incorporated in the US as a tax-exempt non-profit organization and a subsidiary "project" of the independent Joint Development Foundation (JDF), also headquartered in Wakefield.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The Alliance intends to release new video codecs as free software under the BSD 2-Clause License.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] It adopted the patent rules of the W3C which mandate technology contributors to disclose all patents that may be relevant and to agree to a royalty-free patent license.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] The Alliance's patent license contains a defensive termination clause to discourage patent lawsuits.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Software development happens in the open using a public source code repository and issue tracking system, and welcomes contributions from the general public.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Contributions have to pass internal reviews and gain consensus for their adoption.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Different sub-groups inside the Alliance handle testing, reviews for IPR/patent problems hardware-friendliness, and editing of specification documents.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] There are two levels of membership: organizations can join as an ordinary member, or as a governing member with a seat on the board of directors.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Confusingly, these are dubbed "founding members" in AOM terminology, although they need not be members since the Alliance was founded.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] There is a broad representation of the video industry among the Alliance members, featuring several hardware, software, and content producers, OTT video distributors, providers of real-time conferencing solutions, and browser vendors.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] Several AOM members have previously worked on MPEG's HEVC and hold patents to it (e.g.
[src:av2-codec/aomedia] BBC, Intel, Cisco, Vidyo, Apple, Microsoft, and Broadcom).
[src:av2-codec/av1] Like VP9, but unlike H.264 (AVC) and H.265 (HEVC), AV1 has a royalty-free licensing model that does not hinder adoption in open-source projects.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AVIF is an image file format that uses AV1 compression algorithms.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The Alliance's motivations for creating AV1 included the high cost and uncertainty involved with the patent licensing of HEVC (also known as H.265), the MPEG-designed codec expected to succeed AVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Additionally, the Alliance's seven founding members – Amazon, Cisco, Google, Intel, Microsoft, Mozilla, and Netflix – announced that the initial focus of the video format would be delivery of high-quality web video.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The official announcement of AV1 came with the press release on the formation of the Alliance for Open Media on 1 September 2015.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Only 42 days before, on 21 July 2015, HEVC Advance's initial licensing offer was announced to be an increase over the royalty fees of its predecessor, AVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In addition to the increased cost, the complexity of the licensing process increased with HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Unlike previous MPEG standards where the technology in the standard could be licensed from a single entity, MPEG LA, when the HEVC standard was finished, two patent pools had been formed with a third pool on the horizon.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In addition, various patent holders were refusing to license patents via either pool, increasing uncertainty about HEVC's licensing.
[src:av2-codec/av1] According to Microsoft's Ian LeGrow, an open-source, royalty-free technology was seen as the easiest way to eliminate this uncertainty around licensing.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The negative effect of patent licensing on free and open-source software has also been cited as a reason for the creation of AV1.
[src:av2-codec/av1] For example, building an H.264 implementation into Firefox would prevent it from being distributed free of charge since licensing fees would have to be paid to MPEG-LA.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Free Software Foundation Europe has argued that FRAND patent licensing practices make the free software implementation of standards impossible due to various incompatibilities with free-software licenses.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Many of the components of the AV1 project were sourced from previous research efforts by Alliance members.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Individual contributors had started experimental technology platforms years before: Xiph's/Mozilla's Daala published code in 2010, Google's experimental VP9 evolution project VP10 was announced on 12 September 2014, and Cisco's Thor was published on 11 August 2015.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Building on the code base of VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques, several of which were developed in these experimental formats.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Many companies are part of Alliance for Open Media, including Samsung, Vimeo, Microsoft, Netflix, Mozilla, AMD, Nvidia, Intel, ARM, Google, Facebook, Cisco, Amazon, Hulu, VideoLAN, Adobe, and Apple.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Apple is an AOMedia governing member, although it joined after the formation.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The management of the AV1 streams has been officially included among the typological videos manageable by Coremedia.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The first version 0.1.0 of the AV1 reference codec was published on April 7, 2016.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Although a soft feature freeze came into effect at the end of October 2017, development continued on several significant features.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The bitstream format, was projected to be frozen in January 2018 but was delayed due to unresolved critical bugs as well as further changes to transformations, syntax, the prediction of motion vectors, and the completion of legal analysis.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The Alliance announced the release of the AV1 bitstream specification on March 28, 2018, along with a reference, software-based encoder and decoder.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 25 June 2018, a validated version 1.0.0 of the specification was released.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On January 8, 2019, a validated *version 1.0.0 with Errata 1* of the specification was released.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Martin Smole from AOM member Bitmovin said that the computational efficiency was the greatest remaining challenge after the bitstream format freeze had been completed.
[src:av2-codec/av1] While working on the format, the encoder was not targeted for production use and speed optimizations were not prioritized.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Consequently, the early version of AV1 was orders of magnitude slower than existing HEVC encoders.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Much of the development effort was consequently shifted towards improving the reference encoder.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In March 2019, it was reported that the speed of the reference encoder had improved greatly and was within the same order of magnitude as encoders for other common formats.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On January 21, 2021, the MIME type of AV1 was defined as `video/AV1`.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The usage of AV1 using this MIME type is restricted to Real-time Transport Protocol purposes only.
[src:av2-codec/av1] For AOM's 10th birthday, the Alliance announced the successor to AV1 called AV2.
[src:av2-codec/av1] It is designed to deliver better compression performance, enhanced support for AR, VR and split-screen usage and support for a wider visual quality range.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 aims to be a video format for the web that is both state-of-the-art and royalty free.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This concern has been raised regarding AV1, and previously VP8, VP9, Theora and IVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The problem is not unique to royalty-free formats, but it uniquely threatens their *status* as royalty-free.
[src:av2-codec/av1] To fulfill the goal of being royalty free, the development process requires that no feature can be adopted before it has been confirmed independently by two separate parties to not infringe on patents of competing companies.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In cases where an alternative to a patent-protected technique is not available, owners of relevant patents have been invited to join the Alliance (even if they were already members of another patent pool).
[src:av2-codec/av1] For example, Alliance members Apple, Cisco, Google, and Microsoft are also licensors in MPEG-LA's patent pool for H.264.
[src:av2-codec/av1] As an additional protection for the royalty-free status of AV1, the Alliance has a legal defense fund to aid smaller Alliance members or AV1 licensees in the event they are sued for alleged patent infringement.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Under patent rules adopted from the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), technology contributors license their AV1-connected patents to anyone, anywhere, anytime based on reciprocity (i.e. as long as the user does not engage in patent litigation).
[src:av2-codec/av1] As a defensive condition, anyone engaging in patent litigation loses the right to the patents of *all* patent holders.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This treatment of intellectual property rights (IPR), and its absolute priority during development, is contrary to extant MPEG formats like AVC and HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] These were developed under an IPR uninvolvement policy by their standardization organisations, as stipulated in the ITU-T's definition of an open standard.
[src:av2-codec/av1] However, MPEG's chairman has argued this practice has to change, which it is: EVC is also set to have a royalty-free subset, and will have switchable features in its bitstream to defend against future IPR threats.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The creation of royalty-free web standards has been a long-stated pursuit for the industry.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In 2007, the proposal for HTML video specified Theora as mandatory to implement.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The reason was that public content should be encoded in freely implementable formats, if only as a "baseline format", and that changing such a baseline format later would be hard because of network effects.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The Alliance for Open Media is a continuation of Google's efforts with the WebM project, which renewed the royalty-free competition after Theora had been surpassed by AVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] For companies such as Mozilla that distribute free software, AVC can be difficult to support as a per-copy royalty is unsustainable given the lack of revenue stream to support these payments in free software (see FRAND § Excluding costless distribution).
[src:av2-codec/av1] Similarly, HEVC has not successfully convinced all licensors to allow an exception for freely distributed software (see HEVC § Provision for costless software).
[src:av2-codec/av1] The performance goals include "a step up from VP9 and HEVC" in efficiency for a low increase in complexity.
[src:av2-codec/av1] NETVC's efficiency goal is 25% improvement over HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The primary complexity concern is for software decoding, since hardware support will take time to reach users.
[src:av2-codec/av1] However, for WebRTC, live encoding performance is also relevant, which is Cisco's agenda: Cisco is a manufacturer of videoconferencing equipment, and their Thor contributions aim at "reasonable compression at only moderate complexity".
[src:av2-codec/av1] It is therefore planned to support the color space from ITU-R Recommendation BT.2020 and up to 12 bits of precision per color component.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 is primarily intended for lossy encoding, although lossless compression is supported as well.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 is a traditional block-based frequency transform format featuring new techniques.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Based on Google's VP9, AV1 incorporates additional techniques that mainly give encoders more coding options to enable better adaptation to different types of input.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The Alliance published a reference implementation written in C and assembly language (`aomenc`, `aomdec`) as free software under the terms of the BSD 2-Clause License.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Development happens in public and is open for contributions, regardless of AOM membership.
[src:av2-codec/av1] When the feature gained some support in the community, the experiment was enabled by default, and ultimately had its flag removed when all of the reviews were passed.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Experiment names were lowercased in the *configure* script and uppercased in conditional compilation flags.
[src:av2-codec/av1] To better and more reliably support HDR and color spaces, corresponding metadata can now be integrated into the video bitstream instead of being signaled in the container.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Frame content is separated into adjacent same-sized blocks referred to as superblocks.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Similar to the concept of a macroblock, superblocks are square-shaped and can either be of size 128×128 or 64×64 pixels.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Superblocks can be divided in smaller blocks according to different partitioning patterns.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The four-way split pattern is the only pattern whose partitions can be recursively subdivided.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This allows superblocks to be divided into partitions as small as 4×4 pixels.
[src:av2-codec/av1] "T-shaped" partitioning patterns are introduced, a feature developed for VP10, as well as horizontal or vertical splits into four stripes of 4:1 and 1:4 aspect ratio.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The available partitioning patterns vary according to the block size, both 128×128 and 8×8 blocks can't use 4:1 and 1:4 splits.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Moreover, 8×8 blocks can't use T-shaped splits.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Two separate predictions can now be used on spatially different parts of a block using a smooth, oblique transition line (*wedge-partitioned prediction*).
[src:av2-codec/av1] This enables more accurate separation of objects without the traditional staircase lines along the boundaries of square blocks.
[src:av2-codec/av1] More encoder parallelism is possible thanks to configurable prediction dependency between tile rows (`ext_tile`).
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 performs internal processing in higher precision (10 or 12 bits per sample), which leads to quality improvement by reducing rounding errors.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This allows the combination of either two inter predictions or an inter and an intra prediction to be used in the same block.
[src:av2-codec/av1] A frame can reference 6 instead of 3 of the 8 available frame buffers for temporal (inter) prediction while providing more flexibility on bi-prediction (`ext_refs`).
[src:av2-codec/av1] The *Warped Motion* (`warped_motion`) and *Global Motion* (`global_motion`) tools in AV1 aim to reduce redundant information in motion vectors by recognizing patterns arising from camera motion.
[src:av2-codec/av1] They implement ideas that were attempted in preceding formats like e.g.
[src:av2-codec/av1] MPEG-4 ASP, albeit with a novel approach that works in three dimensions.
[src:av2-codec/av1] There can be a set of warping parameters for a whole frame offered in the bitstream, or blocks can use a set of implicit local parameters that get computed based on surrounding blocks.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Intra prediction consists of predicting the pixels of given blocks only using information available in the current frame.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Most often, intra predictions are built from the neighboring pixels above and to the left of the predicted block.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The DC predictor builds a prediction by averaging the pixels above and to the left of block.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Directional predictors extrapolate these neighboring pixels according to a specified angle.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In AV1, 8 main directional modes can be chosen.
[src:av2-codec/av1] These modes start at an angle of 45 degrees and increase by a step size of 22.5 degrees up until 203 degrees.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Furthermore, for each directional mode, six offsets of 3 degrees can be signaled for bigger blocks, three above the main angle and three below it, resulting in a total of 56 angles (`ext_intra`).
[src:av2-codec/av1] The "TrueMotion" predictor was replaced with a Paeth predictor which looks at the difference from the known pixel in the above-left corner to the pixel directly above and directly left of the new one and then chooses the one that lies in direction of the smaller gradient as predictor.
[src:av2-codec/av1] A palette predictor is available for blocks with up to 8 dominant colors, such as some computer screen content.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Correlations between the luminosity and the color information can now be exploited with a predictor for chroma blocks that is based on samples from the luma plane (`cfl`), a technique borrowed from Daala.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In order to reduce visible boundaries along borders of inter-predicted blocks, a technique called overlapped block motion compensation (OBMC) can be used.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This involves extending a block's size so that it overlaps with neighboring blocks by 2 to 32 pixels, and blending the overlapping parts together.
[src:av2-codec/av1] It can combine two one-dimensional transforms in order to use different transforms for the horizontal and the vertical dimension (`ext_tx`).
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 has new optimized quantization matrices (`aom_qm`).
[src:av2-codec/av1] The eight sets of quantization parameters that can be selected and signaled for each frame now have individual parameters for the two chroma planes and can use spatial prediction.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On every new superblock, the quantization parameters can be adjusted by signaling an offset.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In-loop filtering combines Thor's constrained low-pass filter and Daala's directional deringing filter into the *Constrained Directional Enhancement Filter*, `cdef`.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This is an edge-directed conditional replacement filter that smooths blocks roughly along the direction of the dominant edge to eliminate ringing artifacts.
[src:av2-codec/av1] There is also the *loop restoration filter* (`loop_restoration`) based on the Wiener filter and self-guided restoration filters to remove blur artifacts due to block processing.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Daala's entropy coder (`daala_ec`), a non-binary arithmetic coder, was selected for replacing VP9's binary entropy coder.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The use of *non-binary* arithmetic coding helps evade patents but also adds bit-level parallelism to an otherwise serial process, reducing clock rate demands on hardware implementations.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This is to say that the effectiveness of modern binary arithmetic coding like CABAC is being approached using a greater alphabet than binary, hence greater speed, as in Huffman code (but not as simple and fast as Huffman code).
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 also gained the ability to adapt the symbol probabilities in the arithmetic coder per coded symbol instead of per frame (`ec_adapt`).
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 has provisions for temporal and spatial scalability.
[src:av2-codec/av1] A first comparison from the beginning of June 2016 found AV1 roughly on par with HEVC, as did one using code from late January 2017.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In April 2017, using the 8 enabled experimental features at the time (of 77 total), Bitmovin was able to demonstrate favorable objective metrics, as well as visual results, compared to HEVC on the *Sintel* and *Tears of Steel* short films.
[src:av2-codec/av1] A follow-up comparison by Jan Ozer of *Streaming Media Magazine* confirmed this, and concluded that "AV1 is at least as good as HEVC now".
[src:av2-codec/av1] Ozer noted that his and Bitmovin's results contradicted a comparison by Fraunhofer Institute for Telecommunications from late 2016 that had found AV1 65.7% less efficient than HEVC, underperforming even H.264/AVC which they concluded as being 10.5% more efficient.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Ozer justified this discrepancy by having used encoding parameters endorsed by each encoder vendor, as well as having more features in the newer AV1 encoder.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Decoding performance was at about half the speed of VP9 according to internal measurements from 2017.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Tests from Netflix in 2017, based on measurements with PSNR and VMAF at 720p, showed that AV1 was about 25% more efficient than VP9 (libvpx).
[src:av2-codec/av1] Tests from Facebook conducted in 2018, based on PSNR, showed that the AV1 reference encoder was able to achieve 34%, 46.2% and 50.3% higher data compression than libvpx-vp9, x264 High profile, and x264 Main profile respectively.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Tests from Moscow State University in 2017 found that VP9 required 31% and HEVC 22% more bitrate than AV1 in order to achieve similar levels of quality.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The AV1 encoder was operating at speed "2500–3500 times lower than competitors" due to the lack of optimization (which was not available at that time).
[src:av2-codec/av1] Tests from University of Waterloo in 2020 found that when using a mean opinion score (MOS) for 2160p (4K) video AV1 had the bitrate saving of 9.5% compared to HEVC and 16.4% compared to VP9.
[src:av2-codec/av1] They also concluded that at the time of the study at 2160p the AV1 video encodes on average took 590× longer compared to encoding with AVC; while HEVC took on average 4.2× longer and VP9 took on average 5.2× longer than AVC respectively.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The best-in-test AV1 encoder, Visionular's Aurora1, in its "slower" preset, was as fast as *x265 veryslow* while saving 50% bitrate over *x264 veryslow*.
[src:av2-codec/av1] CapFrameX tested the GPUs performance with AV1 decoding.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 5 October 2022, Cloudflare announced that it has a beta player.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 defines three profiles for decoders which are Main, High, and Professional.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The Main profile allows for a bit depth of 8 or 10 bits per sample with 4:0:0 (greyscale) and 4:2:0 (quarter) chroma sampling.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The High profile further adds support for 4:4:4 chroma sampling (no subsampling).
[src:av2-codec/av1] The Professional profile extends capabilities to full support for 4:0:0, 4:2:0, 4:2:2 (half) and 4:4:4 chroma sub-sampling with 8, 10 and 12 bit color depths.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 defines levels for decoders with maximum variables for levels ranging from 2.0 to 6.3.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The levels that can be implemented depend on the hardware capability.
[src:av2-codec/av1] A "Level 7" is mentioned but is not defined.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 video is usually accompanied with AAC or Opus audio in an ISO base media file format (MP4) container.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In October 2016, Netflix stated they expected to be an early adopter of AV1.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 5 February 2020, Netflix began using AV1 to stream select titles on Android, providing 20% improved compression efficiency over their VP9 streams.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 9 November 2021, Netflix announced it had begun streaming AV1 content to a number of TVs with AV1 decoders as well as the PlayStation 4 Pro.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In December 2025 they reported that 30% of their streams use AV1.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In 2018, YouTube began deploying AV1, starting with its AV1 Beta Launch Playlist.
[src:av2-codec/av1] According to the description, the videos are (to begin with) encoded at high bitrate to test decoding performance, and YouTube has "ambitious goals" for rolling out AV1.
[src:av2-codec/av1] YouTube for Android TV supports playback of videos encoded in AV1 on capable platforms as of version 2.10.13, released in early 2020.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In 2020, YouTube started serving videos at 8K resolution in AV1.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In February 2019, Facebook followed its own positive test results, by saying it would gradually roll out the AV1 codec as soon as browser support emerges, starting with its most popular videos.
[src:av2-codec/av1] MSVP (Meta Scalable Video Processor) was announced and the symposis was published in a popular scientific research website on 15 October 2022.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 4 November 2022, the AV1 codec was announced with the article of Meta technology blog and with Mark Zuckerberg on Instagram Reels which shows AV1 codec compared with H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Citing "Our Instagram engineering team developed a way to dramatically improve video quality.
[src:av2-codec/av1] We made basic video processing 94% faster." Android has preliminary native AV1 playback.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In June 2019, Vimeo's videos in the "Staff picks" channel were available in AV1 and Opus.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Vimeo is using and contributing to Mozilla's Rav1e encoder and expects, with further encoder improvements, to eventually provide AV1 support for all videos uploaded to Vimeo as well as the company's "Live" offering.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 30 April 2020, iQIYI announced support for AV1 for users on PC web browsers and Android devices, according to the announcement, as the first Chinese video streaming site to adopt the codec.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Twitch deployed AV1 for its most popular content in 2022 or 2023, with universal support projected to arrive in 2024 or 2025.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In April 2021, Roku removed the YouTube TV app from the Roku streaming platform after a contract expired.
[src:av2-codec/av1] It was later reported that Roku streaming devices do not use processors that support the AV1 codec.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In December 2021, YouTube and Roku agreed to a multiyear deal to keep both the YouTube TV app and the YouTube app on the Roku streaming platform.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Roku had argued that using processors in their streaming devices that support the royalty-free AV1 codec would increase costs to consumers.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In January 2022, Bilibili rolled out H.265 HEVC and AV1 encoding to videos with high view-count, while videos with lower view-count are only available in H.264 AVC.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In July 2024, DMM.com deployed AV1 on its DMM.TV service, becoming the first Japanese company to do so.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Other vendors had announced encoders, including EVE for AV1, NGCodec, Socionext, Aurora and MilliCast.
[src:av2-codec/av1] There are several hardware accelerators for AV1, typically as part of a GPU or system on a chip.
[src:av2-codec/av1] For example, later-generation NVidia GPUs have dedicated hardware and the NVENC and NVDEC APIs for encoding and decoding AV1 and other codecs.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In early 2019, Sisvel, a Luxembourg-based company, claimed to be forming a patent pool of patents essential to AV1.
[src:av2-codec/av1] This development has not caused Google to reevaluate its planned AV1 usage and the Alliance for Open Media has stated they remain confident that AV1 still overcomes the environment of "high patent royalty requirements and licensing uncertainty".
[src:av2-codec/av1] Sisvel began selling licenses to the pool, which contains patents from Philips, GE, NTT, Ericsson, Dolby, and Toshiba in 2020.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Unified Patents has been tracking challenges to various patents in the pool.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 7 July 2022, it was revealed that the European Union's antitrust regulators had opened an investigation into AOM and its licensing policy.
[src:av2-codec/av1] It said this action may be restricting the innovators' ability to compete with the AV1 technical specification, and may eliminate incentives for them to innovate.
[src:av2-codec/av1] On 23 May 2023, the European Commission decided to close the investigation while taking no further action.
[src:av2-codec/av1] But in an email they reiterated that the closure does not constitute a finding of compliance or non-compliance with EU antitrust laws.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In October 2023, patent pool operator Avanci announced the start of a new licensing program targeting video streaming operators that use AV1 in addition to H.265, H.266, VP9, etc.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In March 2026, Dolby sued Snapchat for Video patent infringement in the United States District Court for the District of Delaware (D.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Snap Inc.)) and in the Rio de Janeiro State Court in Brazil (Case no.
[src:av2-codec/av1] In May 2026, the 5th Business Court of Rio de Janeiro granted Dolby IP Bridge preliminary injunction against Skyworth.
[src:av2-codec/av1] The judge baned implementation of patented technologies in current and upcomming products sold in Brazil.
[src:av2-codec/av1] Also in the same month Malikie Innovations sued TCL Technology over AV1 patents in United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas.
[src:av2-codec/av1] AV1 Image File Format (AVIF) is an image file format specification for storing still images or image sequences compressed with AV1 in the HEIF file format.
[src:av2-codec/av1] It competes with HEIC which uses the same container format, built upon ISOBMFF, but HEVC for compression.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Motion compensation is one of the two key video compression techniques used in video coding standards, along with the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Most video coding standards, such as the H.26x and MPEG formats, typically use motion-compensated DCT hybrid coding, known as block motion compensation (BMC) or motion-compensated DCT (MC DCT).
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Motion compensation exploits the fact that, often, for many frames of a movie, the only difference between one frame and another is the result of either the camera moving or an object in the frame moving.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In reference to a video file, this means much of the information that represents one frame will be the same as the information used in the next frame.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Using motion compensation, a video stream will contain some full (reference) frames; then, the only information stored for the frames in between would be the information needed to transform the previous frame into the next frame.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The following is a simplistic illustrated explanation of how motion compensation works.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Two successive frames were captured from the movie *Elephants Dream*.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] As can be seen from the images, the bottom (motion compensated) difference between two frames contains significantly less detail than the prior images, and thus compresses much better than the rest.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In MPEG, images are predicted from previous frames (P frames) or bidirectionally from previous and future frames (B frames).
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] B frames are more complex because the image sequence must be transmitted and stored out of order so that the future frame is available to generate the B frames.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] After predicting frames using motion compensation, the coder finds the residual, which is then compressed and transmitted.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] It works best for still scenes without moving objects.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] MPEG-4 ASP supports global motion compensation with three reference points, although some implementations can only make use of one.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] A single reference point only allows for translational motion, which, for its relatively large performance cost, provides little advantage over block-based motion compensation.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Moving objects within a frame are not sufficiently represented by global motion compensation.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Thus, local motion estimation is also needed.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] To exploit the redundancy between neighboring block vectors (e.g., for a single moving object covered by multiple blocks), it is common to encode only the difference between the current and previous motion vector in the bit-stream.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The result of this differentiating process is mathematically equivalent to a global motion compensation capable of panning.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Further down the encoding pipeline, an entropy coder will take advantage of the resulting statistical distribution of the motion vectors around the zero vector to reduce the output size.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] It is possible to shift a block by a non-integer number of pixels, which is called *sub-pixel precision*.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The in-between pixels are generated by interpolating neighboring pixels.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Commonly, half-pixel or quarter-pixel precision (Qpel, used by H.264 and MPEG-4/ASP) is used.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The computational expense of sub-pixel precision is much higher due to the extra processing required for interpolation and on the encoder side, a much greater number of potential source blocks to be evaluated.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The main disadvantage of block motion compensation is that it introduces discontinuities at the block borders (blocking artifacts).
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The source blocks typically overlap in the source frame.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Some video compression algorithms assemble the current frame out of pieces of several different previously transmitted frames.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Frames can also be predicted from future frames.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The future frames then need to be encoded before the predicted frames and thus, the encoding order does not necessarily match the real frame order.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Such frames are usually predicted from two directions, i.e., from the I- or P-frames that immediately precede or follow the predicted frame.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] These bidirectionally predicted frames are called *B-frames*.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] A coding scheme could, for instance, be IBBPBBPBBPBB.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Further, the use of triangular tiles has also been proposed for motion compensation.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Under this scheme, the frame is tiled with triangles, and the next frame is generated by performing an affine transformation on these triangles.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Only the affine transformations are recorded/transmitted.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] This is capable of dealing with zooming, rotation, translation etc.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Studies of methods for reducing the complexity of OBMC have shown that the contribution to the window function is smallest for the diagonally-adjacent block.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Reducing the weight for this contribution to zero and increasing the other weights by an equal amount leads to a substantial reduction in complexity without a large penalty in quality.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In such a scheme, each pixel then belongs to 3 blocks rather than 4, and rather than using 8 neighboring blocks, only 4 are used for each block to be compensated.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In motion compensation, quarter or half samples are actually interpolated sub-samples caused by fractional motion vectors.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Based on the vectors and full-samples, the sub-samples can be calculated by using bicubic or bilinear 2-D filtering.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] See subclause 8.4.2.2 "Fractional sample interpolation process" of the H.264 standard.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Motion compensation is utilized in stereoscopic video coding.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In video, *time* is often considered as the third dimension.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Still, image coding techniques can be expanded to an extra dimension.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] JPEG 2000 uses wavelets, and these can also be used to encode motion without gaps between blocks in an adaptive way.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Fractional pixel affine transformations lead to bleeding between adjacent pixels.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] If no higher internal resolution is used the delta images mostly fight against the image smearing out.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The delta image can also be encoded as wavelets, so that the borders of the adaptive blocks match.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] 2D+Delta Encoding techniques utilize H.264 and MPEG-2 compatible coding and can use motion compensation to compress between stereoscopic images.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] A precursor to the concept of motion compensation dates back to 1929, when R.D.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Kell in Britain proposed the concept of transmitting only the portions of an analog video scene that changed from frame-to-frame.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In 1959, the concept of inter-frame motion compensation was proposed by NHK researchers Y.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Tanaka, who proposed predictive inter-frame video coding in the temporal dimension.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Practical motion-compensated video compression emerged with the development of motion-compensated DCT (MC DCT) coding, also called block motion compensation (BMC) or DCT motion compensation.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] This is a hybrid coding algorithm, which combines two key data compression techniques: discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding in the spatial dimension, and predictive motion compensation in the temporal dimension.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] DCT coding is a lossy block compression transform coding technique that was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed, who initially intended it for image compression, in 1972.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In 1974, Ali Habibi at the University of Southern California introduced hybrid coding, which combines predictive coding with transform coding.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] However, his algorithm was initially limited to intra-frame coding in the spatial dimension.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Robinson extended Habibi's hybrid coding algorithm to the temporal dimension, using transform coding in the spatial dimension and predictive coding in the temporal dimension, developing inter-frame motion-compensated hybrid coding.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] In 1977, Wen-Hsiung Chen developed a fast DCT algorithm with C.H.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Jain further developed motion-compensated DCT video compression, also called block motion compensation.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] This led to Chen developing a practical video compression algorithm, called motion-compensated DCT or adaptive scene coding, in 1981.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Motion-compensated DCT later became the standard coding technique for video compression from the late 1980s onwards.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The first digital video coding standard was H.120, developed by the CCITT (now ITU-T) in 1984.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] H.120 used motion-compensated DPCM coding, which was inefficient for video coding, and H.120 was thus impractical due to low performance.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] The H.261 standard was developed in 1988 based on motion-compensated DCT compression, and it was the first practical video coding standard.
[src:av2-codec/motion-compensation] Since then, motion-compensated DCT compression has been adopted by all the major video coding standards (including the H.26x and MPEG formats) that followed.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] In transform coding, knowledge of the application is used to choose information to discard, thereby lowering its bandwidth.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] The remaining information can then be compressed via a variety of methods.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] When the output is decoded, the result may not be identical to the original input, but is expected to be close enough for the purpose of the application.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] One of the most successful transform encoding system is typically not referred to as such—the example being NTSC color television.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] After an extensive series of studies in the 1950s, Alda Bedford showed that the human eye has high resolution only for black and white, somewhat less for "mid-range" colors like yellows and greens, and much less for colors on the end of the spectrum, reds and blues.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] Using this knowledge allowed RCA to develop a system in which they discarded most of the blue signal after it comes from the camera, keeping most of the green and only some of the red; this is chroma subsampling in the YIQ color space.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] The result is a signal with considerably less content, one that would fit within existing 6 MHz black-and-white signals as a phase modulated differential signal.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] The average TV displays the equivalent of 350 pixels on a line, but the TV signal contains enough information for only about 50 pixels of blue and perhaps 150 of red.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] This is not apparent to the viewer in most cases, as the eye makes little use of the "missing" information anyway.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] The PAL and SECAM systems use nearly identical or very similar methods to transmit colour.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] In any case both systems are subsampled.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] The term is much more commonly used in digital media and digital signal processing.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] The most widely used transform coding technique in this regard is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, and presented by Ahmed with T.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] This DCT, in the context of the family of discrete cosine transforms, is the DCT-II.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] It is the basis for the common JPEG image compression standard, which examines small blocks of the image and transforms them to the frequency domain for more efficient quantization (lossy) and data compression.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] In video coding, the H.26x and MPEG standards modify this DCT image compression technique across frames in a motion image using motion compensation, further reducing the size compared to a series of JPEGs.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] In audio coding, MPEG audio compression analyzes the transformed data according to a psychoacoustic model that describes the human ear's sensitivity to parts of the signal, similar to the TV model.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] MP3 uses a hybrid coding algorithm, combining the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) and fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] It was succeeded by Advanced Audio Coding (AAC), which uses a pure MDCT algorithm to significantly improve compression efficiency.
[src:av2-codec/transform-coding] The basic process of digitizing an analog signal is a kind of transform coding that uses sampling in one or more domains as its transform.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A **video coding format** (or sometimes **video compression format**) is an encoded format of digital video content, such as in a data file or bitstream.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It typically uses a standardized video compression algorithm, most commonly based on discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding and motion compensation.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A computer software or hardware component that compresses or decompresses a specific video coding format is a video codec.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Some video coding formats are documented by a detailed technical specification document known as a **video coding specification**.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Some such specifications are written and approved by standardization organizations as technical standards, and are thus known as a **video coding standard**.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] There are *de facto* standards and formal standards.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Video content encoded using a particular video coding format is normally bundled with an audio stream (encoded using an audio coding format) inside a multimedia container format such as AVI, MP4, FLV, RealMedia, or Matroska.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] As such, the user normally does not have a H.264 file, but instead has a video file, which is an MP4 container of H.264-encoded video, normally alongside AAC-encoded audio.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Multimedia container formats can contain one of several different video coding formats; for example, the MP4 container format can contain video coding formats such as MPEG-2 Part 2 or H.264.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A *format* is the layout plan for data produced or consumed by a *codec*.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Although video coding formats such as H.264 are sometimes referred to as *codecs*, there is a clear conceptual difference between a specification and its implementations.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Video coding formats are described in specifications, and software, firmware, or hardware to encode/decode data in a given video coding format from/to uncompressed video are implementations of those specifications.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] As an analogy, the video coding format H.264 (specification) is to the codec OpenH264 (specific implementation) what the C Programming Language (specification) is to the compiler GCC (specific implementation).
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Note that for each specification (e.g., H.264), there can be many codecs implementing that specification (e.g., x264, OpenH264, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC products and implementations).
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] This distinction is not consistently reflected terminologically in the literature.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The H.264 specification calls H.261, H.262, H.263, and H.264 *video coding standards* and does not contain the word *codec*.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The Alliance for Open Media clearly distinguishes between the AV1 video coding format and the accompanying codec they are developing, but calls the video coding format itself a *video codec specification*.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The VP9 specification calls the video coding format VP9 itself a *codec*.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] As an example of conflation, Chromium's and Mozilla's pages listing their video formats support both call video coding formats, such as H.264 *codecs*.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A video coding format does not dictate all algorithms used by a codec implementing the format.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] For example, a large part of how video compression typically works is by finding similarities between video frames (block-matching) and then achieving compression by copying previously-coded similar subimages (such as macroblocks) and adding small differences when necessary.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Finding optimal combinations of such predictors and differences is an NP-hard problem, meaning that it is practically impossible to find an optimal solution in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] For example, section 0.5 of the H.264 specification says that encoding algorithms are not part of the specification.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Free choice of algorithm also allows different space–time complexity trade-offs for the same video coding format, so a live feed can use a fast but space-inefficient algorithm, and a one-time DVD encoding for later mass production can trade long encoding-time for space-efficient encoding.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The concept of analog video compression dates back to 1929, when R.D.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Kell in Britain proposed the concept of transmitting only the portions of the scene that changed from frame-to-frame.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The concept of digital video compression dates back to 1952, when Bell Labs researchers B.M.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Harrison proposed the use of differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM) in video coding.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] In 1967, University of London researchers A.H.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Cherry proposed run-length encoding (RLE), a lossless compression scheme, to reduce the transmission bandwidth of analog television signals.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The earliest digital video coding algorithms were either for uncompressed video or used lossless compression; both methods were inefficient and impractical for digital video coding.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Digital video was introduced in the 1970s, initially using uncompressed pulse-code modulation (PCM), requiring high bitrates around 45–200 Mbit/s for standard-definition (SD) video, which was up to 2,000 times greater than the telecommunication bandwidth (up to 100 kbit/s) available until the 1990s.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Similarly, uncompressed high-definition (HD) 1080p video requires bitrates exceeding 1 Gbit/s, significantly greater than the bandwidth available in the 2000s.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Practical video compression emerged with the development of motion-compensated DCT (MC DCT) coding, also called block motion compensation (BMC) or DCT motion compensation.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] DCT coding is a lossy block compression transform coding technique that was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed, who initially intended it for image compression, while he was working at Kansas State University in 1972.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It was then developed into a practical image compression algorithm by Ahmed with T.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Rao at the University of Texas in 1973, and was published in 1974.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The other key development was motion-compensated hybrid coding.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] He examined several transform coding techniques, including the DCT, Hadamard transform, Fourier transform, slant transform, and Karhunen-Loeve transform.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The DCT was applied to video encoding by Wen-Hsiung Chen, who developed a fast DCT algorithm with C.H.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Fralick in 1977, and founded Compression Labs to commercialize DCT technology.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Jain further developed motion-compensated DCT video compression.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] H.120 was not usable in practice, as its performance was too poor.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] H.120 used motion-compensated DPCM coding, a lossless compression algorithm that was inefficient for video coding.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] During the late 1980s, a number of companies began experimenting with discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding, a much more efficient form of compression for video coding.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The CCITT received 14 proposals for DCT-based video compression formats, in contrast to a single proposal based on vector quantization (VQ) compression.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The H.261 standard was developed based on motion-compensated DCT compression.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] H.261 was the first practical video coding standard, and uses patents licensed from a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT, and Toshiba, among others.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Since H.261, motion-compensated DCT compression has been adopted by all the major video coding standards (including the H.26x and MPEG formats) that followed.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] MPEG-1, developed by the Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG), followed in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed with patents licensed from a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Its motion-compensated DCT algorithm was able to achieve a compression ratio of up to 100:1, enabling the development of digital media technologies such as video on demand (VOD) and high-definition television (HDTV).
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] In 1999, it was followed by MPEG-4/H.263, which was a major leap forward for video compression technology.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It uses patents licensed from a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The most widely used video coding format as of 2019 is H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It was developed in 2003, and uses patents licensed from a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] In contrast to the standard DCT used by its predecessors, AVC uses the integer DCT.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] H.264 is one of the video encoding standards for Blu-ray Discs; all Blu-ray Disc players must be able to decode H.264.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A main problem for many video coding formats has been patents, making it expensive to use or potentially risking a patent lawsuit due to submarine patents.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The motivation behind many recently designed video coding formats, such as Theora, VP8, and VP9 have been to create a (libre) video coding standard covered only by royalty-free patents.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Patent status has also been a major point of contention for the choice of which video formats the mainstream web browsers will support inside the HTML video tag.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] The current-generation video coding format is HEVC (H.265), introduced in 2013.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] AVC uses the integer DCT with 4x4 and 8x8 block sizes, and HEVC uses integer DCT and DST transforms with varied block sizes between 4x4 and 32x32.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] HEVC is heavily patented, mostly by Samsung Electronics, GE, NTT, and JVCKenwood.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It is challenged by the AV1 format, intended for free license.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] As of 2019, AVC is by far the most commonly used format for the recording, compression, and distribution of video content, used by 91% of video developers, followed by HEVC, which is used by 43% of developers.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Consumer video is generally compressed using lossy video codecs, since that results in significantly smaller files than lossless compression.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Some video coding formats are designed explicitly for either lossy or lossless compression, and some video coding formats such as Dirac and H.264 support both.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Uncompressed video formats, such as *Clean HDMI*, is a form of lossless video used in some circumstances, such as when sending video to a display over an HDMI connection.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Some high-end cameras can also capture video directly in this format.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Interframe compression complicates editing of an encoded video sequence.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] One example is Motion JPEG, which is simply a sequence of individually JPEG-compressed images.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] This approach is quick and simple, at the expense of the encoded video being much larger than a video coding format supporting Inter frame coding.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Because interframe compression copies data from one frame to another, if the original frame is simply cut out (or lost in transmission), the following frames cannot be reconstructed properly.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Making cuts in intraframe-compressed video while video editing is almost as easy as editing uncompressed video: one finds the beginning and ending of each frame, and simply copies bit-for-bit each frame that one wants to keep, and discards the frames one does not want.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] Another difference between intraframe and interframe compression is that, with intraframe systems, each frame uses a similar amount of data.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] In most interframe systems, certain frames (such as I-frames in MPEG-2) are not allowed to copy data from other frames, so they require much more data than other frames nearby.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It is possible to build a computer-based video editor that spots problems caused when I frames are edited out while other frames need them.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] This has allowed newer formats like HDV to be used for editing.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] However, this process demands a lot more computing power than editing intraframe compressed video with the same picture quality.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] But, this compression is not very effective to use for any audio format.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A video coding format can define optional restrictions to encoded video, called profiles and levels.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] It is possible to have a decoder that only supports decoding a subset of profiles and levels of a given video format, for example, to make the decoder program/hardware smaller, simpler, or faster.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A *profile* restricts which encoding techniques are allowed.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] For example, the H.264 format includes the profiles *baseline*, *main* and *high* (and others).
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] While P-slices (which can be predicted based on preceding slices) are supported in all profiles, B-slices (which can be predicted based on both preceding and following slices) are supported in the *main* and *high* profiles but not in *baseline*.
[src:av2-codec/video-coding-format] A *level* is a restriction on parameters such as maximum resolution and data rates.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 is the successor to VP8 and competes mainly with MPEG's High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC/H.265).
[src:av2-codec/vp9] At first, VP9 was mainly used on Google's video platform YouTube.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The emergence of the Alliance for Open Media, and its support for the ongoing development of the successor AV1, of which Google is a part, led to growing interest in the format.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In contrast to HEVC, VP9 support is common among modern web browsers (see HTML video § Browser support).
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Android has supported VP9 since version 4.4 KitKat, while Safari 14 added support for VP9 in iOS / iPadOS / tvOS 14 and macOS Big Sur.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Parts of the format are covered by patents held by Google.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The company grants free usage of its own related patents based on reciprocity, i.e. as long as the user does not engage in patent litigations.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 is the last official iteration of the TrueMotion series of video formats that Google bought in 2010 for $134 million together with the company On2 Technologies that created it.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The development of VP9 started in the second half of 2011 under the development names of *Next Gen Open Video* (*NGOV*) and *VP-Next*.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The design goals for VP9 included reducing the bit rate by 50% compared to VP8 while maintaining the same video quality, and aiming for better compression efficiency than the MPEG High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC) standard.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In June 2013 the "profile 0" of VP9 was finalized, and two months later Google's Chrome browser was released with support for VP9 video playback.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In October of that year a native VP9 decoder was added to FFmpeg, and to Libav six weeks later.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Mozilla added VP9 support to Firefox in March 2014.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In 2014 Google added two high bit depth profiles: profile 2 and profile 3.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In 2013 an updated version of the WebM format was published, featuring support for VP9 together with Opus audio.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In March 2013, the MPEG Licensing Administration dropped an announced assertion of disputed patent claims against VP8 and its successors after the United States Department of Justice started to investigate whether it was acting to unfairly stifle competition.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Throughout, Google has worked with hardware vendors to get VP9 support into silicon.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In January 2014, Ittiam, in collaboration with ARM and Google, demonstrated its VP9 decoder for ARM Cortex devices.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Using GPGPU techniques, the decoder was capable of 1080p at 30fps on an Arndale Board.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In early 2015 Nvidia announced VP9 support in its Tegra X1 SoC, and VeriSilicon announced VP9 Profile 2 support in its Hantro G2v2 decoder IP.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In April 2015 Google released a significant update to its libvpx library, with version 1.4.0 adding support for 10-bit and 12-bit bit depth, 4:2:2 and 4:4:4 chroma subsampling, and VP9 multithreaded decoding/encoding.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In December 2015, Netflix published a draft proposal for including VP9 video in an MP4 container with MPEG Common Encryption.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In January 2016, Ittiam demonstrated an OpenCL based VP9 encoder.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The encoder is targeting ARM Mali mobile GPUs and was demonstrated on a Samsung Galaxy S6.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 support was added to Microsoft's web browser Edge in 2016.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In March 2017, Ittiam announced the completion of a project to enhance the encoding speed of libvpx.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The speed improvement was said to be 50-70%, and the code "publicly available as part of libvpx".
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 is customized for video resolutions greater than 1080p (such as UHD) and also enables lossless compression.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] It supports resolutions up to 65536×65536, whereas HEVC supports resolutions up to 8192×4320 pixels.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The VP9 format supports the following color spaces (and corresponding YCbCr to RGB transformation matrices): Rec.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 supports many transfer functions and supports HDR video with hybrid log–gamma (HLG) or perceptual quantizer (PQ).
[src:av2-codec/vp9] An early comparison that took varying encoding speed into account showed x265 to narrowly beat libvpx at the very highest quality (slowest encoding) whereas libvpx was superior at any other encoding speed, by SSIM.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] By contrast, another subjective comparison from 2014 concluded that at higher quality settings HEVC and VP9 were tied at a 40 to 45% bitrate advantage over H.264.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Netflix, after a large test in August 2016, concluded that libvpx was 20% less efficient than x265, but by October the same year also found that tweaking encoding parameters could "reduce or even reverse the gap between VP9 and HEVC".
[src:av2-codec/vp9] At NAB 2017, Netflix shared that they had switched to the *EVE* encoder, which according to their studies offered better two-pass rate control and was 8% more efficient than libvpx.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] It was concluded that libvpx and x265 were both capable of the claimed 50% bitrate improvement over H.264, but only at 10–20 times the encoding time of x264.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Judged by the objective quality metric VQM in early 2015, the VP9 reference encoder delivered video quality on par with the best HEVC implementations.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] A decoder comparison by the same developer showed 10% faster decoding for ffvp9 than ffh264 for same-quality video, or "identical" at same bitrate.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] It also showed that the implementation can make a difference, concluding that "ffvp9 beats libvpx consistently by 25–50%".
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Another decoder comparison indicated 10–40 percent higher CPU load than H.264 (but does not say whether this was with ffvp9 or libvpx), and that on mobile, the Ittiam demo player was about 40 percent faster than the Chrome browser at playing VP9.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 is a traditional block-based transform coding format.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The bitstream format is relatively simple compared to formats that offer similar bitrate efficiency like HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 has many design improvements compared to VP8.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Its biggest improvement is support for the use of coding units of 64×64 pixels.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] This is especially useful with high-resolution video.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Also, the prediction of motion vectors was improved.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In addition to VP8's four modes (average/"DC", "true motion", horizontal, vertical), VP9 supports six oblique directions for linear extrapolation of pixels in intra-frame prediction.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In order to enable some parallel processing of frames, video frames can be split along coding unit boundaries into up to four rows of 256 to 4096 pixels wide evenly spaced tiles with each tile column coded independently.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] This is mandatory for video resolutions in excess of 4096 pixels.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] A tile header contains the tile size in bytes so decoders can skip ahead and decode each tile row in a separate thread.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The image is then divided into coding units called superblocks of 64×64 pixels which are adaptively subpartitioned in a quadtree coding structure.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] They can be subdivided either horizontally or vertically or both; square (sub)units can be subdivided recursively down to 4×4 pixel blocks.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Subunits are coded in raster scan order: left to right, top to bottom.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Starting from each key frame, decoders keep 8 frames buffered to be used as reference frames or to be shown later.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Transmitted frames signal which buffer to overwrite and can optionally be decoded into one of the buffers without being shown.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The encoder can send a minimal frame that just triggers one of the buffers to be displayed ("skip frame").
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Each inter frame can reference up to three of the buffered frames for temporal prediction.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Up to two of those reference frames can be used in each coding block to calculate a sample data prediction, using spatially displaced (motion compensation) content from a reference frame or an average of content from two reference frames ("compound prediction mode").
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The (ideally small) remaining difference (delta encoding) from the computed prediction to the actual image content is transformed using a DCT or ADST (for edge blocks) and quantized.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Something like a b-frame can be coded while preserving the original frame order in the bitstream using a structure named superframes.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Hidden alternate reference frames can be packed together with an ordinary inter frame and a skip frame that triggers display of previous hidden altref content from its reference frame buffer right after the accompanying p-frame.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 enables lossless encoding by transmitting at the lowest quantization level (q index 0) an additional 4×4-block encoded Walsh–Hadamard transformed (WHT) residue signal.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In order to be seekable, raw VP9 bitstreams have to be encapsulated in a container format, for example Matroska (.mkv), its derived WebM format (.webm) or the Duck IVF format which is traditionally supported by libvpx, a library that originated at The Duck Corporation.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 is identified as `V_VP9` in WebM and `VP09` in MP4, adhering to respective naming conventions.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Adobe Flash, which traditionally used VPx formats up to VP7, was never upgraded to VP8 or VP9, but instead to H.264.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Therefore, VP9 penetrated web applications only with the shift from Flash to HTML5 technology, which was still somewhat immature when VP9 was introduced.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] A main user of VP9 is Google's popular video platform YouTube, which offers VP9 video at all resolutions along with Opus audio in the WebM file format, through DASH streaming.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Another early adopter was Wikipedia (specifically Wikimedia Commons, which hosts multimedia files across Wikipedia's subpages and languages).
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Wikipedia endorses open and royalty-free multimedia formats.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] As of 2016, the three accepted video formats are VP9, VP8 and Theora.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Since December 2016, Netflix has used VP9 encoding for their catalog, alongside H.264 and HEVC.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] As of February 2020, AV1 has been started to be adopted for mobile devices, not unlike how VP9 has started on the platform.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Google TV uses (at least in part) VP9 profile 2 with Widevine DRM.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Stadia used VP9 for video game streaming up to 4k on supported hardware like the Chromecast Ultra, mobile phones as well as web browsers.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] A series of cloud encoding services offer VP9 encoding, including Amazon, Bitmovin, Brightcove, castLabs, JW Player, Telestream, and Wowza.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Encoding.com has offered VP9 encoding since Q4 2016, which amounted to a yearly average of 11% popularity for VP9 among its customers that year.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] JW Player supports VP9 in its widely used software-as-a-service HTML video player.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] VP9 is supported in all major open source media player software, including VLC, MPlayer/MPlayer2/MPV, Kodi, MythTV, and FFplay.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Android has had VP9 software decoding since version 4.4 "KitKat".
[src:av2-codec/vp9] For a list of consumer electronics with hardware support, including TVs, smartphones, set top boxes and game consoles, see webmproject.org's list.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Hardware accelerated VP9 decoding support nowadays is ubiquitous as most GPUs and SoCs support it natively.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Hardware encoding is present in Intel's Kaby Lake processors and above.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The Sony PlayStation 5 supports capturing 1080p and 2160p footage using VP9 in a WebM container.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The reference implementation from Google is found in the free software programming library `libvpx`.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] It has a single-pass and a two-pass encoding mode, but the single-pass mode is considered broken and does not offer effective control over the target bitrate.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] FFmpeg's VP9 decoder takes advantage of a corpus of SIMD optimizations shared with other codecs to make it fast.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] A comparison made by an FFmpeg developer indicated that this was faster than libvpx, and compared to FFmpeg's h.264 decoder, "identical" performance for same-bitrate video, or about 10% faster for same-quality video.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In March 2019, Luxembourg-based Sisvel announced the formation of patent pools for VP9 and AV1.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Members of the pools included JVCKenwood, NTT, Orange S.A., Philips, and Toshiba, all of whom were also licensing patents to the MPEG-LA for either the AVC, DASH, or the HEVC patent pools.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] A list of claimed patents was first published on 10 March 2020.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Sisvel's prices are .24 Euros for display devices and .08 Euros for non-display devices using VP9, but would not seek royalties for encoded content.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] However, their license makes no exemption for software.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] On September 12, 2014, Google announced that development on VP10 had begun and that after the release of VP10 they planned to have an 18-month gap between releases of video formats.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] In August 2015, Google began to publish code for VP10.
[src:av2-codec/vp9] However, Google decided to incorporate VP10 into AOMedia Video 1 (AV1).
[src:av2-codec/vp9] The AV1 codec was developed based on a combination of technologies from VP10, Daala (Xiph/Mozilla) and Thor (Cisco).
[src:av2-codec/vp9] Accordingly, Google has stated that they will not deploy VP10 internally nor officially release it, making VP9 the last of the VPx-based codecs to be released by Google.
